---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import { Code } from 'astro:components';
---

<Layout title="Getting Started -- mailypoppins" description="Install mailypoppins and send your first email in under 5 minutes.">
  <Nav />
  <main id="main-content" class="content page">
    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>Getting Started</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Install mailypoppins and send your first email in under 5 minutes.</p>
    </header>

    <!-- Installation -->
    <section>
      <h2>Installation</h2>

      <h3>Homebrew (macOS and Linux)</h3>
      <p>
        <em>Available once the first tagged release ships.</em> Installs a
        prebuilt binary -- no Rust toolchain needed:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock lang="bash" code="brew install sylvainhellin/email/mailypoppins" />

      <h3>Prebuilt binaries</h3>
      <p>
        <em>Available once the first tagged release ships.</em> Download the
        archive for your platform (macOS arm64/x86_64, Linux x86_64 gnu or
        static musl) from the
        <a href="https://github.com/sylvainhellin/mailypoppins/releases" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub Releases page</a>,
        verify the <code>.sha256</code> checksum, and place the
        <code>email</code> binary somewhere on your <code>PATH</code>.
      </p>

      <h3>From source</h3>
      <p>
        You need the Rust toolchain installed. If you don't have it yet, install it from
        <a href="https://rustup.rs" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rustup.rs</a>.
        Then clone the repository and build:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        lang="bash"
        code={`git clone https://github.com/sylvainhellin/mailypoppins
cd mailypoppins
cargo install --path .`}
      />
      <p>
        This installs the <code>email</code> binary to <code>~/.cargo/bin/</code>.
        Make sure that directory is in your <code>PATH</code>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Setup -->
    <section>
      <h2>Setup</h2>
      <p>Run the interactive setup wizard:</p>
      <CodeBlock lang="bash" code="email config init" />
      <p>The wizard walks through these steps:</p>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>Choose a provider: standard IMAP/SMTP, Microsoft 365 with OAuth2, or Graph API.</li>
        <li>Enter credentials (server host, port, username, email address).</li>
        <li>Automatic connection test to verify everything works.</li>
        <li>Mailbox discovery: the wizard lists server mailboxes and lets you assign the inbox, archive, and sent roles.</li>
        <li>Config is written to <code>~/.config/email/config.toml</code>.</li>
        <li>Password is stored securely in the OS keyring (macOS Keychain, Windows Credential Manager, or Linux Secret Service).</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        For Microsoft 365 accounts, the wizard runs the OAuth2 device code flow: it
        displays a URL and a code, you sign in via your browser, and the token is
        cached locally.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- First Sync -->
    <section>
      <h2>First Sync</h2>
      <p>After setup, pull your emails from the server:</p>
      <CodeBlock lang="bash" code="email sync" />
      <p>
        This syncs all configured mailboxes (inbox, archive, sent, plus any extras).
        Each email is saved as a <code>.md</code> file with YAML frontmatter and an
        accompanying <code>.html</code> file. Attachments are saved in a sibling
        <code>_attachments/</code> directory.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sync is additive by default: it only downloads new messages, deduplicating by
        Message-ID. Add <code>--reconcile</code> to also detect server-side moves and
        deletes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Launch the TUI -->
    <section>
      <h2>Launch the TUI</h2>
      <p>Run the binary with no arguments to open the interactive terminal UI:</p>
      <CodeBlock lang="bash" code="email" />
      <p>
        The TUI shows a sidebar with your mailboxes, an email list, and a headers/body
        preview pane. Core navigation:
      </p>
      <ul class="key-list">
        <li><code>j</code> / <code>k</code> to move up and down the email list</li>
        <li><code>1</code>-<code>9</code> to jump to a mailbox by index</li>
        <li><code>Enter</code> or <code>e</code> to open an email in your <code>$EDITOR</code></li>
        <li><code>/</code> to filter, <code>\</code> to search (includes body text)</li>
        <li><code>?</code> for the full help overlay</li>
        <li><code>q</code> to quit</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The TUI watches your inbox in the background (via IMAP IDLE or Graph polling)
        and fetches new mail automatically when it arrives.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Your First Draft -->
    <section>
      <h2>Your First Draft</h2>
      <p>
        The draft workflow goes through three stages: <code>draft</code> (writing),
        <code>approved</code> (reviewed), and <code>sent</code> (delivered). Here is
        the end-to-end flow from the CLI:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        lang="bash"
        code={`# Create a new draft
email new meeting-followup

# Open and edit the file in your editor -- fill in recipients, subject, body

# Mark it as reviewed and ready to send
email mark-approved ~/notes/email/drafts/meeting-followup.md

# Send it
email send ~/notes/email/drafts/meeting-followup.md`}
      />
      <p>Or from the TUI:</p>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>Press <code>n</code> to create a new draft. It opens in your <code>$EDITOR</code>.</li>
        <li>Write your email in Markdown with YAML frontmatter (to, subject, body).</li>
        <li>Save and close the editor. The draft appears in the list.</li>
        <li>Press <code>A</code> to mark it as approved.</li>
        <li>Press <code>x</code> to send. Confirm when prompted.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>A draft file looks like this:</p>
      <CodeBlock
        lang="yaml"
        filename="meeting-followup.md"
        code={`---
to: colleague@example.com
cc: team@example.com
subject: "Meeting follow-up"
status: draft
---

Hi,

Here are the action items from today's meeting:

- Item one
- Item two

Let me know if I missed anything.`}
      />
    </section>

    <!-- What's Next -->
    <section>
      <h2>What's Next</h2>
      <ul class="next-links">
        <li><a href="/commands/">Commands</a> -- full reference for every CLI command</li>
        <li><a href="/draft-format/">Draft Format</a> -- frontmatter fields, status workflow, attachments</li>
        <li><a href="/config/">Configuration</a> -- multi-account setup, OAuth2, Graph API, signatures</li>
        <li><a href="/faq/">FAQ</a> -- troubleshooting and common questions</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .page {
    padding-top: var(--space-16);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-16);
  }

  .page-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
  }

  .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    color: var(--color-subtext0);
  }

  section {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
  }

  .steps {
    list-style: decimal;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    color: var(--color-subtext1);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .steps li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .key-list {
    list-style: disc;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    color: var(--color-subtext1);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .key-list li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .next-links {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .next-links li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--color-subtext1);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .next-links a {
    color: var(--color-mauve);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .next-links a:hover {
    color: var(--color-peach);
  }
</style>
